15/01 - what I did - Yesterday only whatched i course of Treversy and now i learning about OOP and how can I use classes in the javascript and now I write what I learned:

1- before 2022 in javascript was impossible to set a property or method and make them private, devs take a '_' in front of property indicates this shouldn't be changed or accessed from outside the class, for n reasons. example is:

 class Bank {
  this._amountBank = 0
 }

_amountBank is a property shouldn't be accessed or changed from outside the class, but now you can set this using the notation "#" and this property changed to private method if you try access this the javascript throw error

2-you can set a method inside the class using only using a key and putting inside a function but it's better putt inside the prototype. the first code is the first way you can do:

const Person{
  walk: function {
    console.log(walk)
  }
}

if you console.log(Person) the type of walk is function and this method don't enter in the prototype, if you do like this way:

Person.prototype.walk = function () {
  console.log(walk)
}

the method enter in the prototype
